  abstract = {We analyse the anisotropic clustering of the Baryon Oscillation Spectroscopic Survey (BOSS) CMASS Data Release 11 (DR11) sample, which consists of \$690\textbackslash,827\$ galaxies in the redshift range \$0.43 {$<$} z {$<$} 0.7\$ and has a sky coverage of \$8\textbackslash,498\textbackslash,\textbackslash text\{deg\}\^2\$. We perform our analysis in Fourier space using a power spectrum estimator suggested by Yamamoto et al. (2006). We measure the multipole power spectra in a self-consistent manner for the first time in the sense that we provide a proper way to treat the survey window function and the integral constraint, without the commonly used assumption of an isotropic power spectrum and without the need to split the survey into sub-regions. The main cosmological signals exploited in our analysis are the Baryon Acoustic Oscillations and the signal of redshift space distortions, both of which are distorted by the Alcock-Paczynski effect. Together, these signals allow us to constrain the distance ratio \$D\_V(z\_\{\textbackslash rm eff\})/r\_s(z\_d) = 13.89\textbackslash pm 0.18\$, the Alcock-Paczynski parameter \$F\_\{\textbackslash rm AP\}(z\_\{\textbackslash rm eff\}) = 0.679\textbackslash pm0.031\$ and the growth rate of structure \$f(z\_\{\textbackslash rm eff\})\textbackslash sigma\_8(z\_\{\textbackslash rm eff\}) = 0.419\textbackslash pm0.044\$ at the effective redshift \$z\_\{\textbackslash rm eff\}=0.57\$. We did not find significant systematic uncertainties for \$D\_V/r\_s\$ or \$F\_\{\textbackslash rm AP\}\$ but include a systematic error for \$f\textbackslash sigma\_8\$ of \$3.1\textbackslash\%\$. Combining our dataset with Planck to test General Relativity (GR) through the simple \$\textbackslash gamma\$-parameterisation, reveals a \$\textbackslash sim 2\textbackslash sigma\$ tension between the data and the prediction by GR. The tension between our result and GR can be traced back to a tension in the clustering amplitude \$\textbacksla