  urldate = {2019-11-19},
  abstract = {In recent years, the Lyman-$\alpha$ absorption observed in the spectra of high-redshift quasars has been used as a tracer of large-scale structure by means of the three-dimensional Lyman-$\alpha$ forest auto-correlation function at redshift zsimeq 2.3, but the need to fit the quasar continuum in every absorption spectrum introduces a broadband distortion that is difficult to correct and causes a systematic error for measuring any broadband properties. We describe a k-space model for this broadband distortion based on a multiplicative correction to the power spectrum of the transmitted flux fraction that suppresses power on scales corresponding to the typical length of a Lyman-$\alpha$ forest spectrum. Implementing the distortion model in fits for the baryon acoustic oscillation (BAO) peak position in the Lyman-$\alpha$ forest auto-correlation, we find that the fitting method recovers the input values of the linear bias parameter b\textsubscript{F} and the redshift-space distortion parameter β\textsubscript{F} for mock data sets with a systematic error of less than 0.5\%. Applied to the auto-correlation measured for BOSS Data Release 11, our method improves on the previous treatment of broadband distortions in BAO fitting by providing a better fit to the data using fewer parameters and reducing the statistical errors on β\textsubscript{F} and the combination b\textsubscript{F}(1+β\textsubscript{F}) by more than a factor of seven. The measured values at redshift z=2.3 are β\textsubscript{F}=1.39\textsuperscript{+0.11 +0.24 +0.38}\textsubscript{-0.10 -0.19 -0.28} and b\textsubscript{F}(1+β\textsubscript{F})=-0.374\textsuperscript{+0.007 +0.013 +0.020}\textsubscript{-0.007 -0.014 -0.022} (1σ, 2σ and 3σ statistical errors). Our fitting software and the input files needed to reproduce our main results are publicly available. {$<$}P /{$>$}},
