  abstract = {We introduce QuasarNET, a deep convolutional neural network that performs classification and redshift estimation of astrophysical spectra with human-expert accuracy. We pose these two tasks as a \textbackslash emph\{feature detection\} problem: presence or absence of spectral features determines the class, and their wavelength determines the redshift, very much like human-experts proceed. When ran on BOSS data to identify quasars through their emission lines, QuasarNET defines a sample \$99.51\textbackslash pm0.03\$\textbackslash\% pure and \$99.52\textbackslash pm0.03\$\textbackslash\% complete, well above the requirements of many analyses using these data. QuasarNET significantly reduces the problem of line-confusion that induces catastrophic redshift failures to below 0.2\textbackslash\%. We also extend QuasarNET to classify spectra with broad absorption line (BAL) features, achieving an accuracy of \$98.0\textbackslash pm0.4\$\textbackslash\% for recognizing BAL and \$97.0\textbackslash pm0.2\$\textbackslash\% for rejecting non-BAL quasars. QuasarNET is trained on data of low signal-to-noise and medium resolution, typical of current and future astrophysical surveys, and could be easily applied to classify spectra from current and upcoming surveys such as eBOSS, DESI and 4MOST.},
