  urldate = {2019-11-18},
  abstract = {We measure the imprint of primordial baryon acoustic oscillations (BAOs) in the correlation function of Ly$\alpha$ absorption in quasar spectra from the Baryon Oscillation Spectroscopic Survey (BOSS) and the extended BOSS (eBOSS) in Data Release 14 (DR14) of the Sloan Digital Sky Survey (SDSS)-IV. In addition to 179 965 spectra with absorption in the Lyman-$\alpha$ (Ly$\alpha$) region, we use Ly$\alpha$ absorption in the Lyman-β region of 56 154 spectra for the first time. We measure the Hubble distance, D\textsubscript{H}, and the comoving angular diameter distance, D\textsubscript{M}, relative to the sound horizon at the drag epoch r\textsubscript{d} at an effective redshift z = 2.34. Using a physical model of the correlation function outside the BAO peak, we find D\textsubscript{H}(2.34)/r\textsubscript{d} = 8.86 ± 0.29 and D\textsubscript{M}(2.34)/r\textsubscript{d} = 37.41 ± 1.86, within 1σ from the flat-ΛCDM model consistent with CMB anisotropy measurements. With the addition of polynomial "broadband" terms, the results remain within one standard deviation of the CMB-inspired model. Combined with the quasar-Ly$\alpha$ cross-correlation measurement presented in a companion paper, the BAO measurements at z = 2.35 are within 1.7σ of the predictions of this model.},
